Sarah</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='36184#1521149552'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2018-03-15T21:32:32+00:00">Mar 15, 2018 09:32 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1521149552">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Carl,

I should have mentioned earlier&#58; I&#39;m migrating from edg-mkgridmap so I&#39;m not able to do that. The gridmap file that I do (/etc/grid-security/grid-mapfile) have contains the local entries I specified (basically local users and an entry for RSV); the rest were created automatically.

1) To clarify, are you asking about a specific user because we&#39;re in central phedex, or is it something different? Looking in the phedex load test directory it seems uscms01, a service user account on our cluster, owns them locally.
2) Files in /store/user are owned by the local account of the user that initiated the transfer/stage out. Files in /store/temp/user are owned by uscms01. The mapping between the local account name and the DN was placed in a file named local-gridmap that was then passed into grid-mapfile.  We like it this way because it allows users to manage their files once they&#39;ve been staged out from CRAB jobs (read&#58; they don&#39;t have to ask a superuser). Can we keep a similar scheme under LCMAPS?

I think I can just create the new accounts; do any of them need root-level permissions?

Thanks,

Jamal

by jrorie@....</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='36184#1521143536'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2018-03-15T19:52:16+00:00">Mar 15, 2018 07:52 PM UTC</time> by <b>clundstedt@....</b><a class="anchor" name="1521143536">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hey Jamal,

To get your current mappings you can use your GUMS server interface to make gridmap and see how things map currently which is what I did to construct a grid-mapfile (with FQDNs) that told me what needed filled in for our local mappings.   I ended up having to transfer about 60 maps to our gridmap file in order to accommodate GUMS localmappings and  pool accounts that had files in /store/user.

There is not a config file that constructs the gridmap/vo-map files, that&#39;s a flat file that encompasses your site&#39;s policies.  We sling our around with puppet so all the mappings are consistent.

I think Carl Edquist with OSG was working on a script to do some of that tedium but I can&#39;t find if that ever came to be.

There&#39;s no OSG side downside to creating the default accounts and I&#39;d encourage you to do that if it&#39;s not arduous.  The only thing that might become an issue is file ownership mismatches in your SE.  The CE activities should be sufficiently independent that new user accounts won&#39;t be a problem for jobs.  Services aren&#39;t really the problem here (unless you have some intricate priority/scheduling at the scheduler level that depends on username), the whole problem comes from file ownerships in your SE.

At Nebraska we converted all our CEs to lcmaps a week or so before converting the SEs since username on the job almost didn&#39;t matter and the SE was still using GUMS so ownerships were consistent.  The things to look at are&#58;
1) How is the cms phedex user&#39;s DN mapping, that need to own all the CMS files in your storage.

2) What users do you have using /store/user /store/temp/user space?  Those files need to be owned by the correct Unix user/DN pair.

Carl Lundstedt

Nebraska</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='36184#1521141163'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2018-03-15T19:12:43+00:00">Mar 15, 2018 07:12 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1521141163">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Carl,

Thanks for the info; it&#39;s good to know I can use the current user accounts. Looking at our list of accounts, though, I don&#39;t see one that clearly is for lcgadmin. That gives me pause.

1) Is there a file besides &#39;/etc/grid-security/voms-mapfile&#39;, which we don&#39;t have, that would contain the current user account mapping configuration for our cluster?
2) Failing that, could you tell me which config files use this information so I can construct a list for the next admin?
3) Finally, would there be any harm in just creating the user accounts listed in /usr/share/osg/voms-mapfile-default and going forward from there? Could that lead to conflicts with previously configured services?

Thanks,

Jamal

by jrorie@....</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='36184#1521134653'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2018-03-15T17:24:13+00:00">Mar 15, 2018 05:24 PM UTC</time> by <b>clundstedt@....</b><a class="anchor" name="1521134653">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hey Jamal,

Those accounts are the ones that ship configured with the stock LCMAPS voms-mapfile.  You can either have those local user accounts or map your existing cms accounts via the voms-mapfile, e.g. Nebraska has&#58;

&#34;/cms/Role=pilot*&#34; cmsprod
&#34;/cms/Role=production*&#34; cmsprod004
&#34;/cms/local/Role=pilot*&#34; uscmsPool036
&#34;/cms/Role=NULL*&#34; uscmsPool001

You can also add local users to grid-mapfile to further customize your lcmaps policies.  As long as they DNs map to some user things should work fine.

We maintain these mapping across all our resources via puppet, so if you stray from the default accounts you&#39;ll have to manage this file somehow.

As for group, I don&#39;t know that it matters but at Nebraska we have a couple of groups for grid users&#58;
group&#58; grid for all generic accounts
group&#58; cmswrite for phedex and other writing cms users
and cmsuser for generic cms accounts.
But it likely doesn&#39;t matter what the groups are as long as it is user like.

Best of luck,
Carl Lundstedt
UNL</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='36184#1521133705'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2018-03-15T17:08:25+00:00">Mar 15, 2018 05:08 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1521133705">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hello Tim,

If I&#39;m reading the instructions correctly, CMS accounts need the following local unix accounts&#58;
cmspilot, uscmslocal, cmslocal, cmsprod, lcgadmin, cmsuser
Additionally, I suspect it&#39;s a good idea to add
osg

What group should these accounts belong to? Does it matter? What privileges do they need?

Thanks,

Jamal

